 To convert Markdown to HTML, you can use a library like `boost-format` for parsing Markdown and `tiny_mudcobain` for rendering HTML. However, since you asked for a solution without using external libraries, here's a simple function that converts some basic Markdown syntax to HTML.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string &markdown) {
    std::regex headingRegex(R"(# {1,6}(.*?)(?=\n(#|$)))");
    std::regex linkRegex(R"(\[(.*?)\]\((.*?)\))");

    std::string html = "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang='en'>\n<head>\n  <meta charset='UTF-8'>\n  <meta name='viewport' content='width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0'>\n  <title>Markdown to HTML</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n";

    std::smatch match;
    std::string replacedText = markdown;

    while (std::regex_search(replacedText, match, headingRegex)) {
        int level = match.str(0).size() - 2;
        std::string header = match.str(1);
        std::string tag = "<h" + std::to_string(level) + ">" + header + "</h" + std::to_string(level) + ">";
        replacedText = std::regex_replace(replacedText, match, tag);
    }

    while (std::regex_search(replacedText, match, linkRegex)) {
        std::string linkText = match.str(1);
        std::string linkUrl = match.str(2);
        std::string tag = "<a href='" + linkUrl + "'>" + linkText + "</a>";
        replacedText = std::regex_replace(replacedText, match, tag);
    }

    html += replacedText;
    html += "</body>\n</html>";

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Heading 1\n## Heading 2\n[Link Text](https://example.com)\n**Bold Text**\n_Italic Text_";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This code will convert the following Markdown syntax to HTML:

- Headers (`#`, `##`, ..., `######`)
- Links (`[Link Text](URL)`)
- Bold text (`**Bold Text**`)
- Italic text (`_Italic Text_`)

Please note that this solution is very basic and does not cover all Markdown syntax. For a more comprehensive solution, consider using a library like `boost-format` or `cpp-markdownlite`.

