 ### Automatically Generated Table of Contents in LaTeX

To automatically generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document, you can use the `\tableofcontents` command after the preamble and before the body of your document. Here's a simple example:

```latex
\documentclass{book} % Use the book class for multi-chapter documents
\usepackage{hyperref} % Include hyperref package for clickable links

\title{My Document}
\author{Author Name}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\maketitle % Print the title, author, and date

\tableofcontents % Generate the table of contents

\chapter{Introduction}
This is the introduction chapter.

\chapter{Chapter One}
This is the first chapter.

\chapter{Chapter Two}
This is the second chapter.

\section{Section One}
This is the first section of Chapter Two.

\section{Section Two}
This is the second section of Chapter Two.

\end{document}
```

### Explanation

1. **Document Class**: The `\documentclass{book}` command specifies the document class. In this case, we're using the `book` class for multi-chapter documents.

2. **Hyperref Package**: The `\usepackage{hyperref}` command is used to enable hyperlinks in the generated PDF.

3. **Title, Author, and Date**: These commands set the title, author, and date of the document.

4. **\maketitle**: This command prints the title, author, and date at the beginning of the document.

5. **\tableofcontents**: This command generates the table of contents.

6. **\chapter and \section**: These commands are used to create chapters and sections in the document.

### Note

- Make sure to include the `hyperref` package before any other packages that may redefine the linking behavior.
- The table of contents will automatically update as you add, remove, or reorder chapters and sections in your document.

